      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the soffritto",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large pot over low-medium heat. Add {{onion}} diced onion, {{celery}} diced celery and {{carrot}} diced carrot. Cook gently for 12 minutes, stirring occasionally, until soft but not coloured. Add {{garlic}} of sliced garlic and cook for 2 more minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add vegetables and simmer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add {{potato}} diced potato, {{courgette}} diced courgette, {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{cannellini-beans}} of beans and {{stock-vegetable}} of stock. Drop in the Parmesan rind. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper. Bring to a simmer and cook for 25 minutes until the potatoes are tender.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the pasta and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add {{pasta-dried}} of small pasta to the pot. If using kale, add it now too. Cook for 8 to 10 minutes until the pasta is just tender. Remove the Parmesan rind. Taste and adjust seasoning. Ladle into deep bowls and finish with a drizzle of extra-virgin olive oil and grated Parmesan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Cook pasta separately and add it to each bowl at serving. The soup base keeps better this way.",
              "cause": "Pasta absorbed liquid and overcame as it sat in the soup.",
              "symptom": "Pasta turned to mush in leftovers"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Mash a ladleful of the beans against the side of the pot and stir back in; it thickens the broth naturally.",
              "cause": "Too much stock, or vegetables cut too large to dissolve starch.",
              "symptom": "Soup thin and watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a rind and simmer an extra 15 minutes. The soffritto needs 12 full minutes to develop sweetness.",
              "cause": "No Parmesan rind, or soffritto undercooked.",
              "symptom": "Flavour flat and lacking depth"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Minestrone is the Italian thrift soup: a meal built from the vegetable drawer and the store cupboard. Every Italian region has a version; every Italian family has adjustments. It is one of those dishes that tastes better the second day, when the flavours have had time to settle. Serve in winter with a thick slice of bread, or in summer with a spoonful of pesto stirred in at the end.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
